body: We don't treat warnings from external libraries as errors, unless something is wrong. For example, on Windows everytime when I compile onnxruntime, I saw tons of C4244 warnings from absl. But they don't fail my build. So, I'm interested to know where the "-Werror" comes from.
And does clang15 support CentOS7? Our ROCM pipeline still uses CentOS 7. Should it be changed? @PeixuanZuo I don't understand what role clang plays here.

If the upcoming hip-clang will be based on clang15, then we need to make sure it works, possibly changing pipelines.
Is this blocking you, or will it block in the future? We are not setting `-Werror`.

I actually met this problem before, when using a homebrew latest hip clang build. Build with `-DCMAKE_CXX_FLAGS=-Wno-deprecated-builtins` will workaround the problem. It is not added to our cmakelists because the `-Wno-deprecated-builtins` is not unknown to old version of hip-clang, causing unknonw flags errors populated.

@snnn The (hip-)clang is AMD flavored clang, with HIP language support. When building HIP code (cu files in `providers/rocm`), if you include `type_traits.h` from absl, maybe transitively, the compile fails, because `-Werror` is enabled for HIP code. You can add some flags checking and then exclude the warning at https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/b731cf397d5ddc584c6af96af2f14221b93c85a3/cmake/CMakeLists.txt#L1310-L1326

I see. "-DCMAKE_CXX_FLAGS=-Wno-deprecated-builtins" is not right. It will override the default CXX flags. For example, if you are doing a release build, you will find "-O2" is missing. Because you define CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS to something, instead of appending something to CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS. 

> either update the abseil-cpp submodule or change the -Wdeprecated-builtins to -Wno-deprecated-builtins.

Yes, we should. Thanks for explanation
It is passed from commandline, not set in cmakelists.

Hi @jeffdaily, I found ROCm5.3.x already used clang-15, but when we use this clang-15 under /opt/rocm/llvm/bin/, onnxruntime build well, why we haven't meet this error yet? Is there any difference between the clang-15 being used in ROCm5.3.x and the clang-15 in upcoming ROCm version? Thanks!

/opt/rocm/llvm/bin/clang++ --version
```
AMD clang version 15.0.0 (https://github.com/RadeonOpenCompute/llvm-project roc-5.3.0 22362 3cf23f77f8208174a2ee7c616f4be23674d7b081)
Target: x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu
Thread model: posix
InstalledDir: /opt/rocm/llvm/bin
```

I didn't have any issue using ROCm 5.3.x either, or our soon-to-be-released ROCm 5.4.  Only our current internal development environment (5.5) faces this issue.  In any case, the error is legitimate.  The workaround I used to unblock our dev teams was https://github.com/ROCmSoftwarePlatform/onnxruntime/commit/53c24ad7d3469511b9d742ca97d024c569a854e5.

EDIT:
I think the correct solution is to update the abseil-cpp submodule, as suggested above.  I didn't submit a PR to do that because I wasn't sure if there would be any unintended consequences.  I didn't see a release version of abseil-cpp available at its project page that contained the fix; the fix only appeared to be in the development branch.  I don't know abseil-cpp well enough to know whether it's development branch is considered stable, or if you need to wait for the next stable release package to be available.

Updating `abseil-cpp` potentially may cause problems with our CUDA compilation (we have a patch) and natvis updates. It is feasible to do, but may take more time than simply updating the version string.

Currently we rely on a commit from one of the release branches of abseil. We shouldn't use a commit from the dev branch esp. when there's a workaround for the issue. As @jeffdaily said we can't tell if the dev branch should be considered stable.

@jeffdaily How is AMD handling the compiling now? In my previous PRs, I moved all HIP code compilation to use native cmake HIP language support. So there will be combinations of compiler usage.
1. `CMAKE_CXX_COMPILER=<gcc>` and `CMAKE_HIP_COMPILER=<hipclang>`, note this is the default if you do not have any config for it
2. `CMAKE_CXX_COMPILER=<hipclang>` and `CMAKE_HIP_COMPILER=<hipclang>`

If you are still in the first category, then you can try to filter the flag `-Wdeprecated-builtins` for HIP translation units in my previous comment (search REMOVE_ITEM in this page). If you fall into the second category, then the only way to go is removing it globaly, maybe condition on when hipclang is used.
